KwaZulu-Natal families who lost everything in the recent floods need all the help they can get. Lindokuhle Xulu has more. Courtesy of #DStv403 NDWENDWE - Environmental Activists say atmospheric CO2 levels are rising, and South Africa must act urgently to prevent a climate crisis. They say in the next 20 to 50 years, we might not have a country to talk of. KwaZulu-Natal is trying to recover from floods which hit mostly coastal areas, killing over 400 people and leaving thousands displaced. READ: 23% of SA water not safe for drinking: report Over 50 people are still missing, while government officials are still tallying the cost of the damage. The African Global Networks NGO is provided the much-needed help to communities left destitute on Friday in the Ndwedwe Municipality. Founder Wiseman Mkhize says they'll also give school uniforms.